out_-    where  is given by .  The spectrum in the
region  is just the free spectrum of the unstable
D-brane, and  is a pure state of open string
excitations. Despite this fact we shall see in section 3 that
 closely resembles a thermal state at temperature .
Indeed we shall see that the results of measurements done after
brane creation differ from thermal results by asymptotically
vanishing amounts.


Full s-brane modes 

For the full s-brane potential , the Klein-Gordon equation is
 &(^2_t + 2l t + ^2) u=0 .  
This is a form of Mathieu's equation. We will now summarize a few
useful properties of the solutions - see e.g. - 
  for more
detail. The solutions are generalized Mathieu functions, which can
be written as
This form for 
differs from the standard convention for Mathieu functions.
Our  is related to the standard
characteristic exponent (often denoted  in the literature) by
.  
  u=&A e^-i  t 
P(t)+ B e^i  t  P(-t)    where the function
 P(t) = _r=- ^  c_2r  e^rt    is
periodic in imaginary time . The constants
 and  obey complicated recursive formulae
and are typically computed numerically.
Although it is not obvious from ,
all solutions  vanish exponentially in the far past and the far
future. This is because open string modes get very massive far
from the interior of the brane.

Solutions to Mathieu's equation are typically classified by their
behavior with respect to imaginary time . A solution is
bounded on the  axis only if  is purely
imaginary. In this case the solution is called stable  -
otherwise it is unstable . Solutions are stable only for
certain regions of the  plane. For large positive
 - the case of interest -  is real and
all solutions are unbounded on the real  axis. However,
there is a unique solution that vanishes as  -
this is the solution with . We will see later that this
solution is naturally associated to the state with no particles in
the interior of the s-brane at .


