The  sD-brane limit 
In this section we will consider the very interesting limits
. In  it was shown that in a certain
 limit, the general bosonic s-brane boundary
state  (at zero temperature) reduces to the boundary state
of  which imposes a Dirichlet boundary condition  in
the time direction. In other words  is an
sD-brane. The relation to sD-branes follows
immediately from the fact that the  boundary
interaction is an  rotation by  which transforms a
Neumann boundary state into a Dirichlet state.

On the other hand, in  it was shown that in a certain
 limit, the general s-brane boundary state in
some sense reduces to nothing - i.e. in this limit
there is no brane present at
all.As can be seen from , the superstring case for both
 and   is qualitatively
similar to the  bosonic case.  In fact, we will
see that the limiting closed string configuration
is not unambiguously
determined from the boundary state for any value of .
Additional boundary conditions
on the fields are needed. In general the limit is not the trivial
one described in , but rather is a very special type of
s-brane configuration described by spacelike Dirichlet branes
located on the imaginary time axis.

In the next subsection, we will describe this ambiguity in the
limit . In section 6.2 we will derive  the
linearized RR-field sourced by an sD-brane and see that it carries
a non-trivial s-charge for all . In 6.3 the long range 
graviton and dilaton fields of an s-brane are computed. In 6.4 we determine
the force between an ordinary D-brane and a 
sD-brane from a computation of the annulus diagram. in 6.5 the
calculation is generalized to finite temperature. Finally, in
section 6.6 we discuss the relation between s-branes and
D-instantons.

The classical closed string field 

Consider the state  C=1 L_0+L_0  B.  This can be viewed as a quantum state of a
single closed string. Alternately, since the states in the Fock
basis of the single closed string are identified as spacetime
components of the classical string field,  can be
viewed as a classical string field configuration. By construction
it obeys (L_0+L_0) C= B. 
These are the linearized spacetime wave equations with sources for
the components of the classical string field. The source is the
boundary state  whose support is confined to the
brane. Hence we conclude that  is the linearized
classical closed string field sourced by the brane.



For ordinary static supersymmetric D-branes, it has been
explicitly verified that  as defined in  reproduces the
linearized dilaton, metric and RR  fields sourced by the
brane . When the brane is static, the Fock component states in
 carry no , and
all of its components are off-shell. A unique static 
 may then be determined from . Time-dependent boundary
states differ crucially in this regard. They have components with
non-vanishing  which correspond to on-shell closed string
states and hence are annihilated by . It follows
that  is not invertible and   is
not unambiguously determined from . This is just
the usual problem of specifying the homogenous part of the
solution emanating from a time-dependent source. Some additional
boundary conditions must be specified.We note that this
closed string ambiguity remains even after we have
fixed the quantum state of the open strings on the brane. 

For general , the Fock components of the string field
wave equation  are of the form 
